author: Francesca Gillett
title: 3.9 magnitude earthquake strikes off coast of North Yorkshire
text:
Tuesday 3 January 2017 21:58 BST North Sea: The earthquake struck around 100 miles from Scarborough in North Yorkshire. Getty Images 
An earthquake has struck off the coast of northern England, it has been reported. 
The 3.9 magnitude earthquake is believed to have hit the North Sea around 100 miles east of Scarborough in Yorkshire on Tuesday evening. 
The British Geological Survey said the earthquake struck at around 6.50pm. 
Seismologists is yet to confirm the tremor but its devices nearby did show activity in the North Sea , reports have said. Read more Scores killed after 6.5 magnitude earthquake hits Indonesia 
Earthquakes of magnitude up to 5.4 can often be felt but only usually cause minor damage. 
Magnitudes of 5.5 and above can cause damage to buildings while any earthquakes above 7 are considered major. More about:
